Bye-bye to accidents with a new strategy Tsuruoka Police Station collaborates with related organizations to raise safety awareness |Yamagata Newspaper
A collision test between a car and a bicycle was conducted at a bicycle class held as a kick-off event for the operation: Shoko Gakuen Driving School, Tsuruoka
Tsuruoka Police Station (Chief Sato Keizo) has launched "Operation Bye Bye Accident Zero" in an attempt to eliminate accidents involving bicycles and motorcycles, which have been occurring at a high rate in the area in recent years.
In addition to working with traffic safety organizations in the prefecture to promote awareness of accident prevention, it will also step up enforcement of violations of traffic rules for bicycles.
There have been three fatal traffic accidents in the precinct this year, in which motorcyclists and bicyclists were killed.
Although the number of accidents has been on a downward trend, the rate of accidents involving bicycles was about 11.7% as of June 30, and the rate of accidents involving motorcycles was about 5.8%, both of which were higher than the prefecture average.
In particular, the rate of bicycle accidents has been higher than the prefectural average in many years over the past five years, and we have planned a strategy to overcome this situation.
The name of the operation is a combination of the words "bike" and "bicycle" with the meaning of eliminating accidents.
Related organizations will be called upon more than ever to provide driving instruction to the elderly and utilize luminous reflective materials in traffic safety classes.
In the event of a crackdown, the station will issue a yellow card (guidance warning ticket) to remind people to be careful.
The launch ceremony for the operation was held at the Shoko Gakuen Driving School in Tsuruoka on the 21st.
There were about 30 people in attendance, and Chief Sato said, "I would like to ask for your cooperation in order to reduce the number of tragic accidents."
A representative from the office explained the policy and the activities of each organization.
As a follow-up event to the start of the operation, a bicycle class was held.
A police officer in a car demonstrated the difference in impact between hitting a bicycle with the brakes on and hitting it at about 55km/h without the brakes on.
Kinouchi Koichi, chairman of the Tsuruoka District Community Traffic Safety Promotion Committee, said, "I once again realized the horror of traffic accidents. I would like to call attention to the elderly as well as young people."
