Sedative drug detected in body of woman with ALS Not available on the market, may have been administered via gastrostomy tube: Hokkaido Shimbun Doshin Online Edition
In a case in which doctors Okubo Yuichi (42) and Yamamoto Naoki (43) were both arrested on suspicion of murder-for-hire after being asked by a female patient with the incurable muscle-wasting disease amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) to administer drugs and kill her, it was revealed in an interview with investigators on the 25th that a "barbiturate-type" sedative had been found in the woman's body.
The prefectural police believe that he was given a sedative from a gastrostomy tube, a tube that delivers nutrition to the stomach.
Barbiturate drugs are used to treat conditions such as epilepsy and are not available over the counter, according to medics.
When administered in large quantities, it can suppress breathing and lead to death, and is used by assisted suicide groups in Europe and the United States.
